1.6.3 Predicate specs
---------------------

Predicates are distinguished by their name _and_ their arity. We will
call `name/arity' a _predicate spec_. The notation `name/arity' is
therefore used when it is necessary to refer to a predicate
unambiguously. For example, `concatenate/3' specifies the predicate
which is named "concatenate" and which takes 3 arguments.

   (Note that different predicates may have the same name and
different arity. Conversely, of course, they may have the same arity
and different name.)


