124.5.3 Lists of bytes and buffers
----------------------------------

A list of bytes (c.f., a list of ints) corresponds to a byte buffer
in C. The length of the buffer is associated to that of the list
using the property `size_of/2'. The returned buffer *is freed by Ciao
Prolog* upon its recepction, unless the `do_not_free/1' property is
specified (see later). Conversely, a list of natural numbers in the
range 0 to 255 can be passed to C as a buffer.

   *File* _byte_lists.pl_:

     :- module(byte_lists, [obtain_list/3, show_list/2], [foreign_interface]).

     :- true pred obtain_list(in(N),go(Length),go(List)) :: int * int * byte_list
             + (foreign,size_of(List,Length)).
     :- true pred show_list(in(Length),in(List)) :: int * byte_list
             + (foreign,size_of(List,Length)).

     :- use_foreign_source(bytes_op).

   *File* _bytes_op.c_:

     #include <stdlib.h>
     #include <stdio.h>

     void obtain_list(int n, int *l, char **s) {
       int i;
       int c;
       if (n < 0) n = 0;
       *l = n;
       *s = (char *)malloc(*l);
       for (i = 0; i < *l; i++) {
         (*s)[i] = i;
       }
     }

     void show_list(int l, char *s) {
       if (s) {
         int n;
         printf("From C:");
         for (n = 0; n < l; n++) {
           printf(" %d", s[n]);
         }
         printf(".\n");
       } else {
         printf("From C: []\n");
       }
     }


